tion while working within its decentralized structure. The resulting relationship encompassed:\n‚Ä¢ Development of Recruitment Long Term Strategy: The long range strategy and business plan centered around five program\nareas (customer interaction, management execution, operational excellence, upgrading talent/skills and service delivery)\n‚Ä¢ Deployment of a Center of Excellence (CoE): The COE centralized recruiting strategic activities that could be standardized across the\nenterprise\n‚Ä¢ Business Case/Internal Support: This included business case development and strategic change management to build internal\nsupport for transforming the recruitment function\n‚Ä¢ Single Applicant Tracking System: Management of a vendor selection process for identifying the talent solution best suited\nto the company‚Äôs unique needs and support a multi-phased implementation based on region deployment\n<h2>Results</h2>\n‚Ä¢ Key recruitment metrics saw vacancy rates decline by 60%, time to fill drop by 25% and customer satisfaction increase by over 20%\n‚Ä¢ On-time/on-budget system implementation with phased deployment across regional organizations\n‚Ä¢ Scalable service delivery model to facilitate talent management strategy throughout the enterprise\n‚Ä¢ Proactive candidate pipeline development now possible with crossenterprise processes\n‚Ä¢ Consistent process and candidate service now ensures an improved recruitment capability and supports a quality employment brand experience', 'Kaiser Permanente', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1222-revision', '', '', '2011-10-11 14:28:19', '2011-10-11 14:28:19', '', 1222, 'http://futurestep.testarea.me.uk/uncategorized/%sub-category%/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1256, 2, '2011-10-12 16:14:32', '2011-10-12 16:14:32', 'Founded in 1945, Kaiser Permanente is the nation‚Äôs largest not-forprofit health plan, serving 8.7 million members. With headquarters in Oakland, California and 160,000 employees across the country, the company is a leader in healthcare and noted for its pioneering role in pre-paid insurance, physicians group practices, prevention and organized service delivery.\n<h2>Challenges</h2>\nIn 2006, the company began looking at ways to increase operational performance of its highly decentralized recruitment function. Driven by a need to lower vacancy rates, time-to-fill, cost-per-fill, and increase customer satisfaction and quality of hire, Kaiser turned to consultants from The Newman Group, a Futurestep Company, for strategic partnership and support. Key operational challenges included:\n<ul>\n	<li>Lack of a Comprehensive Strategy: No single strategy that could create organizational alignment and target key infrastructure issues that needed to be addressed</li>\n	<li>Disparate Processes: A decentralized recruitment organization, including eight separate regions and a corporate recruitment organization</li>\n	<li>Separate Systems: Multiple, disparate applicant tracking systems with minimal HRIS integration</li>\n	<li>A Variety of Stakeholders: Multiple organizational leaders, each with a significant role in the overall recruitment strategy</li>\n	<li>Need to Manage to Metrics: A need to create organizational consistency, clarity and accountability regarding key recruitment metrics</li>\n	<li>Need for Enterprise Advantage: A strong push to improve resource allocation for strategic activities that could be consistent across the enterprise</li>\n	<li>Improve Candidate, Pipeline and Customer Results: A need to improve brand consistency, achieve a proactive pipeline and increase manager satisfaction</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Approach</h2>\nTalent strategy experts from The Newman Group/Futurestep worked with Kaiser to develop a plan that would transform the recruitment function while working within its decentralized structure. The resulting relationship encompassed:\n<ul>\n	<li>Development of Recruitment Long Term Strategy: The long range strategy and business plan centered around five program areas (customer interaction, management execution, operational excellence, upgrading talent/skills and service delivery)</li>\n	<li>Deployment of a Center of Excellence (CoE): The COE centralized recruiting strategic activities that could be standardized across the enterprise</li>\n	<li>Business Case/Internal Support: This included business case development and strategic change management to build internal support for transforming the recruitment function</li>\n	<li>Single Applicant Tracking System: Management of a vendor selection process for identifying the talent solution best suited to the company‚Äôs unique needs and support a multi-phased implementation based on region deployment</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Results</h2>\n<ul>\n	<li>Key recruitment metrics saw vacancy rates decline by 60%, time to fill drop by 25% and customer satisfaction increase by over 20%</li>\n	<li>On-time/on-budget system implementation with phased deployment across regional organizations</li>\n	<li>Scalable service delivery model to facilitate talent management strategy throughout the enterprise</li>\n	<li>Proactive candidate pipeline development now possible with cross enterprise processes</li>\n	<li>Consistent process and candidate service now ensures an improved recruitment capability and supports a quality employment brand experience</li>\n</ul>', 'Kaiser Permanente', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1222-autosave', '', '', '2011-10-12 16:14:32', '2011-10-12 16:14:32', '', 1222, 'http://futurestep.testarea.me.uk/uncategorized/%sub-category%/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1275, 2, '2011-10-10 14:48:58', '2011-10-10 14:48:58', 'Thanks to the evolution of RPO, companies have more choices than ever for implementing strategies that address their unique needs‚Äîbut more choices mean more to consider. How do you arrive at the right RPO strategy? What should you expect? Where are the pitfalls? What are the opportunities for value?\r\n\r\nIn this session, RPO experts Jeanne MacDonald and Paul Flavin of Futurestep explore best practices for implementing an RPO that aligns with business goals. When it comes to implementation, a business perspective is essential. What does it take to establish the right process? Do you need to relook at centralized versus decentralized talent acquisition operations? What about global concerns? Where do you need consistency, where do you need regional flexibility? How do you establish the plan for action and make the business case you need for support across the organization? To transition from implementation to operations, the experience of companies that have done it before provides a valuable perspective. Where have companies succeeded in tying RPO to business needs? Where have they fallen short? Where have companies faced challenges and successfully adjusted to overcome them?\r\n\r\nFinally, when it comes to monitoring and measurement, companies have tremendous needs. How are they tying RPO performance to relevant business goals? What are the metrics for success? How are they tracking performance, and how are they ensuring that the impact is being reflected back to the leadership that is critical to a successful RPO operation. From operational efficiency to quality of hire‚Äîwe‚Äôll look at the innovations and results. For anyone exploring the opportunity for the first time for their organization, or embarking on a ‚Äúsecond generation‚Äù RPO, this session will provide valuable insight on what is driving success today, and how to achieve lasting impact into the future.', 'Maximizing Your Investment: Implement RPO to Align with Business Goals', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '904-revision-16', '', '', '2011-10-10 14:48:58', '2011-10-10 14:48:58', '', 904, 'http://futurestep.testarea.me.uk/uncategorized/%sub-category%/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
