(1260, 1, '2011-10-11 14:45:58', '2011-10-11 14:45:58', 'Founded in 1945, Kaiser Permanente is the nation‚Äôs largest not-forprofit health plan, serving 8.7 million members. With headquarters in Oakland, California and 160,000 employees across the country, the company is a leader in healthcare and noted for its pioneering role in pre-paid insurance, physicians group practices, prevention and organized service delivery.\r\n<h2>Challenges</h2>\r\nIn 2006, the company began looking at ways to increase operational performance of its highly decentralized recruitment function. Driven by a need to lower vacancy rates, time-to-fill, cost-per-fill, and increase customer satisfaction and quality of hire, Kaiser turned to consultants from The Newman Group, a Futurestep Company, for strategic partnership and support. Key operational challenges included:\r\n‚Ä¢ Lack of a Comprehensive Strategy: No single strategy that could create organizational alignment and target key infrastructure issues that needed to be addressed\r\n‚Ä¢ Disparate Processes: A decentralized recruitment organization, including eight separate regions and a corporate recruitment organization\r\n‚Ä¢ Separate Systems: Multiple, disparate applicant tracking systems with minimal HRIS integration\r\n‚Ä¢ A Variety of Stakeholders: Multiple organizational leaders, each with a significant role in the overall recruitment strategy\r\n‚Ä¢ Need to Manage to Metrics: A need to create organizational consistency, clarity and accountability regarding key recruitment metrics\r\n‚Ä¢ Need for Enterprise Advantage: A strong push to improve resource allocation for strategic activities that could be consistent across the enterprise\r\n‚Ä¢ Improve Candidate, Pipeline and Customer Results: A need to improve brand consistency, achieve a proactive pipeline and increase manager satisfaction\r\n<h2>Approach</h2>\r\nTalent strategy experts from The Newman Group/Futurestep worked with Kaiser to develop a plan that would transform the recruitment function while working within its decentralized structure. The resulting relationship encompassed:\r\n‚Ä¢ Development of Recruitment Long Term Strategy: The long range strategy and business plan centered around five program areas (customer interaction, management execution, operational excellence, upgrading talent/skills and service delivery)\r\n‚Ä¢ Deployment of a Center of Excellence (CoE): The COE centralized recruiting strategic activities that could be standardized across the enterprise\r\n‚Ä¢ Business Case/Internal Support: This included business case development and strategic change management to build internal support for transforming the recruitment function\r\n‚Ä¢ Single Applicant Tracking System: Management of a vendor selection process for identifying the talent solution best suited to the company‚Äôs unique needs and support a multi-phased implementation based on region deployment\r\n<h2>Results</h2>\r\n‚Ä¢ Key recruitment metrics saw vacancy rates decline by 60%, time to fill drop by 25% and customer satisfaction increase by over 20%\r\n‚Ä¢ On-time/on-budget system implementation with phased deployment across regional organizations\r\n‚Ä¢ Scalable service delivery model to facilitate talent management strategy throughout the enterprise\r\n‚Ä¢ Proactive candidate pipeline development now possible with crossenterprise processes\r\n‚Ä¢ Consistent process and candidate service now ensures an improved recruitment capability and supports a quality employment brand experience', 'Kaiser Permanente', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1222-revision-4', '', '', '2011-10-11 14:45:58', '2011-10-11 14:45:58', '', 1222, 'http://futurestep.testarea.me.uk/uncategorized/%sub-category%/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
